Japan's economy contracted by a record 4% in the first quarter of the year as domestic demand and investment buckled – but many economists believe that the worst is now over for the world's second-largest economy.The Japanese government said yesterday that GDP had plunged 15% on 2008 levels in the first three months of this year – the steepest fall since records began in 1955 and the fourth consecutive quarter of decline.Japan, which is heavily dependent on the electronics sales and exports has been hit by the collapse in demand from the US, Europe and China. Exports plummeted by a record 26% in the first three months of 2009.However, economists at Daiwa Securities SMBC believe there are tentative signs of recovery. "The worst of the downturn may have played out," they said.